<img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-1569409 lazyload lazyload" src="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Hair-wash-day.-Photo-Getty-scaled.jpg" alt="" width="1280" height="853" srcset="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Hair-wash-day.-Photo-Getty-scaled.jpg 2560w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Hair-wash-day.-Photo-Getty-898x598.jpg 898w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Hair-wash-day.-Photo-Getty-1729x1152.jpg 1729w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Hair-wash-day.-Photo-Getty-1536x1023.jpg 1536w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Hair-wash-day.-Photo-Getty-2048x1364.jpg 2048w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Hair-wash-day.-Photo-Getty-320x213.jpg 320w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Hair-wash-day.-Photo-Getty-640x426.jpg 640w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Hair-wash-day.-Photo-Getty-600x400.jpg 600w" sizes="(max-width: 1280px) 100vw, 1280px" /> Every good conditioner has one essential ingredient, cetrimonium chloride, and we bet that if you checked the ingredients of your favourite conditioner, it’s definitely there.   Cetrimonium chloride is solely responsible for leaving your hair soft and well detangled and ensuring your curls are as bouncy as ever. This is because it is often used as an emulsifier that keeps ingredients blended to ensure they work together while its antiseptic properties prevent the growth of microorganisms that could ruin your products. This is an all you need to know guide about your new best friend, cetrimonium chloride and why it is the secret ingredient to a great hair conditioner. Benefits of Cetrimonium Chloride in Haircare When included in conditioners, cetrimonium chloride carries out multiple functions within the formulation. By acting as a cationic surfactant, it allows other ingredients within the conditioner to function properly. That’s not all it does; it also: Cetrimonium chloride smoothens the hair cuticles by softening them, allowing them to be easily detangled and leaving a silky ouch. As a surfactant, it helps ensure that the oil and water in the conditioner work well together, which is necessary for cleansing and conditioning the hair. Cetrimonium chloride also functions as an emulsifier unifying other ingredients within the product to result in a smoothly blended shampoo, conditioner, or leave-in product. Not all ingredients in your hair products have a long shelf life. So by adding cetrimonium chloride, all bacteria are kept at bay, extending the product’s shelf life and allowing you to use it for longer. Cetrimonium chloride makes for a great anti-frizz, anti-static agent on cold days. Its positive chemical bond attracts the negative charges in the hair during cold weather, which allows it neutralizes this static. What type of hair does it work for? Any hair type can enjoy the benefit of cetrimonium chloride. To use correctly, opt for rinse-off products, stylers, detanglers, and leave-in conditioners with a concentration of no more than 0.25%. As anything higher may stimulate sensitive scalps. Regular use of the products with cetrimonium chloride also guarantees maximum benefits.  